  "doc_id": "20476",
  "text": "The difficulty that a number of deciduous fruit trees have in adapting to environmental conditions different from those of their origin is well known and is mainly the result of the need for adequate satisfaction of their chilling requirements for flowering. Problems related to the inaccurate selection of cultivars with unsuitable chilling requirements affect japanese apricot production. Many growers used winter chilling accumulation to determine the timeline for certain management measures, such as the spraying of rest-breaking chemical agents, or to predict yield potential [CITATION_1] .",
